    "summary": "The founding of the Khmer Empire (c. 802 AD) — when King Jayavarman II performed a ritual declaring himself a universal monarch (chakravartin) at Mount Kulen in Cambodia, breaking from Javanese suzerainty and establishing an independent kingdom — marks the beginning of one of Southeast Asia's greatest civilizations, which would eventually build Angkor Wat and govern an empire covering modern Cambodia, Thailand, Laos, and parts of Vietnam. The Khmer Empire (802–1431 AD) was the dominant land power of mainland Southeast Asia for over six centuries.\n\nJayavarman II introduced the devaraja cult (divine king) — the identification of the king with the Hindu deity Shiva, embodied in a sacred linga (phallus) kept in a temple mountain at the capital — which became the ideological foundation of Khmer kingship. Each Khmer king built a temple-mountain as his state temple and prospective mausoleum, competing in scale with predecessors; this royal competition produced the extraordinary temple complexes of the Angkor region, culminating in [[event:3782|Angkor Wat]] (built by Suryavarman II, c. 1113–1150 AD) — the largest religious building ever constructed. Khmer hydraulic engineering — an enormous system of reservoirs (barays) and canals that enabled year-round rice cultivation — supported a population of perhaps one million in the Angkor region alone. The [[event:2962|precursors to Angkor]] in the preceding centuries set the stage for this monumental achievement.",
    "wikipedia_url": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Khmer_Empire",
